lues or values outside the scale range ## (`geom_path()`). 10.9 What the code shows The script does four things. It defines a nonlinear system for distress and coping. It searches numerically for equilibrium points from multiple starting guesses. It computes the Jacobian and classifies each equilibrium using eigenvalues. It simulates trajectories from several initial conditions and overlays them on a vector field. This workflow is useful because nonlinear systems may have multiple equilibria, and analytical solutions are not always convenient. Numerical root-finding and simulation let us move from formalism to interpretation. 10.10 Interpreting the phase portrait In a stable regime, trajectories from different initial conditions converge toward the same equilibrium. Distress may briefly rise or coping may briefly fall, but the system eventually settles. This corresponds to resilience in the dynamical sense: perturbations decay. In a fragile regime, trajectories may separate sharply depending on where they begin. Some recover, others move away, and the equilibrium acts like a threshold rather than a destination. That picture resembles the idea of tipping points in mental health, where a system can remain apparently manageable until a disturbance pushes it into a very different pattern. 10.11 Cautions about interpretation A model like this should be treated as a conceptual scaffold, not a literal clinical theory. Mental health is shaped by biology, development, relationships, culture, institutions, treatment access, and chance. No two-dimensional system can represent all of that. Still, simple models can be valuable. They make assumptions explicit, clarify feedback structure, and help us distinguish questions about equilibrium, local stability, thresholds, and recovery time. They are especially useful when the goal is understanding mechanism rather than prediction. 10.12 Closing perspective The language of equilibrium points and linear stability gives us a mathematically precise way to talk about resilience and fragility. A stable equilibrium represents a state that absorbs disturbance. A saddle point marks a threshold. Complex eigenvalues signal oscillatory adjustment. The Jacobian tells us how self-reinforcement and cross-coupling shape those outcomes. In mental health applications, that perspective can be illuminating. It suggests that distress is not merely something that rises or falls in isolation; it interacts continuously with coping, recovery, and feedback. Once those interactions are formalized, stability becomes something we can analyze rather than merely describe.
